        output='Based on the provided prospectus preamble excerpts, here are the definitions, caveats, and limitations for Monthly Active Users (MAUs), daily posts, and broader user engagement metrics across the X and Grok platforms.\n\n### 1. Monthly Active Users (MAUs)\n**Definition:** \nMAU is defined as the total number of registered users who have interacted with Grok or X through web browsers or mobile applications at least once during the 30-day period ending on the date of measurement. \n\n**Methodology & Inclusions:**\n*   **Registration Requirement:** Only users who have formally registered for an X or Grok account are included in this metric.\n*   **Deduplication:** When presenting *combined* MAUs across both platforms, the company attempts to identify and account for users who access both Grok and X based on sign-in traffic to prevent double-counting.\n*   **Feature Tracking:** The company tracks the specific subset of MAUs who utilize Grok’s AI features versus those who do not, based on the source of their server requests.\n\n**Caveats & Limitations:**\n*   **Estimation & Duplication:** The methodology only provides a "reasonable approximation" of unique users. It may not fully capture all instances of cross-platform duplication, meaning reported MAUs should be viewed strictly as an *estimate*.\n*   **Strategic Deprioritization:** The company explicitly states that it manages the business to drive sustainable revenue growth, operating margin, and profitability. Therefore, growing or maintaining MAU levels is *not* a primary business objective.\n*   **Market Fluctuations:** In the highly competitive consumer AI market, usage metrics and app downloads for Grok can fluctuate significantly (including periods of decline) due to competitor model releases, product update cycles, and shifts in user behavior.\n\n### 2. Daily Posts\n**Definition:** \n"Daily posts" refers to the aggregate daily volume of original posts, replies, reposts, quotes, and media shared by users on the X platform, combined with the real-time interactions, analysis, and generative capabilities provided to a user by Grok. \n\n**Inclusions:**\n*   **AI-Generated Content:** The metric explicitly includes posts and content generated by AI or accounts managed by AI.\n*   **Volume:** The text notes this real-time information stream consists of approximately 350 million daily posts.\n\n**Caveats & Limitations:**\n*   **Content Limitations for AI Training:** While this massive dataset is used to ground Grok’s "truth-seeking" capabilities in up-to-date knowledge and diverse viewpoints, the company notes that its use of the X dataset is "subject to some limitations for certain content."\n*   **Quality Dependency:** The value of this metric is heavily dependent on user-generated content. If users stop contributing, or if the platform is flooded with problematic/offensive content, the utility of this data stream for AI development and advertiser engagement degrades.\n\n### 3. User Engagement Metrics (Broadly)\n**Definition & Tracking:**\n*   **Supported Accounts:** The company tracks "supported accounts active in the last twelve months" (noted as over 1.3 billion) as a broader measure of the ecosystem\'s total reachable scale.\n*   **Monetizable Engagement:** Engagement is tracked to facilitate high-impact advertising inventory, performance-based marketing tools, and unified user experiences across communication, content discovery, commerce, and financial services.\n\n**Caveats, Risks & Limitations:**\n*   **Platform Migration Risk:** Engagement metrics are highly vulnerable to user migration. Losing users to competing platforms directly negatively impacts potential subscription and advertising revenues.\n*   **The "Content-Engagement-AI" Flywheel Risk:** There is a critical downstream limitation tied to engagement. If user engagement declines, or if content quality drops (e.g., offensive material), it not only harms X\'s brand reputation and monetizable usage but also *starves the ongoing development of the Grok AI product*, which relies on X\'s real-time data and user-generated content to maintain its competitive differentiator.\n*   **Intense Competition for Attention:** The company warns that the consumer AI and social media markets are characterized by an "intense competition for user attention," making long-term engagement stability inherently uncertain and subject to rapid shifts in consumer preferences. \n\n### Summary\nThe prospectus makes it clear that while **MAUs** and **Daily Posts** are massive in scale (550M MAUs and 350M daily posts), they are treated as *inputs* for revenue and AI training rather than vanity metrics to be grown at all costs. The primary limitations revolve around the technical difficulties of perfectly deduplicating cross-platform users, the inclusion of AI-generated noise in post volumes, and the severe downstream business risks if user engagement or content quality on X were to decline.',
